Originally, my friends and I were looking to go to Upstairs at 66 where they had games. We didn’t realize it was located upstairs at Route 66 (which makes sense when you think about it) but the game room was closed for a private event. So we decided to just sit downstairs, order some drinks (HH is 4-7) and a few apps to share since none of us were too hungry.  For drinks, I stuck to the house whiskey ginger - which wasn’t bad. They don’t skimp on the alcohol, which a lot of happy hour places do, so I appreciate that. For food, we had the Cracklin’ Pork Clouds (pork rinds) - really good, especially dipped in their green sauce, Sarah’s smoked wings - salty AF; I was only able to eat one piece, the Truffle Brussels - one of their “specials” but it wasn’t special, and some regular fries - soggy and oily.  I guess you don’t really come to Stone Street to eat. Stick to the drinks here and hopefully, the game room upstairs will be open when you go.

A vibey place. I like the location and the decor. The music was good. I took off a star because the pork ribs were not up to standard, very fatty, and not much flavour. The barbecue sauce tasted like salad dressing because all I tasted was balsamic vinegar. Not quite something you want to mix with your meat. And I took off another star because we ordered the side of fries which came warm-ish and they were not good fries, and the coleslaw which we were told was creamy but in fact the sauce was like water, in essence we were eating soggy cabbage. And the soda was flat. Upon complaining about my dish, the manager took it off the bill even though we asked her not to. She really tried to make up for it. Lovely staff. I’d go back, but not for the ribs.

The upstairs is super fun the list of games are as follows: 5 foot tall jenga, 5 foot tall connect four, they had several game systems( Sega genesis, Nintendo switch with smash bros and Mario party,) several arcade games, ping pong table and a foosball table just to name a few.

The fries especially was so hard and tasted like it was fried up more than 10 times although the sea salt did help a little but I still cannot eat it.
